Scope of the Standard

Shunyaya Structural Substrate Layer (SSSL) defines a structural regime algebra over scalar magnitude evolution.

SSSL establishes:

Finite structural alphabet:

A4 = {Z0, Eplus, S, Eminus}

Conservative collapse invariant:

phi((m,a,s)) = m

Deterministic structural mapping:

a_i = F(E_i, dE_dt_i, discharge_i)

where:

dE_dt_i = (E_i - E_{i-1}) / Delta_t (uniform sampling assumed)

Deterministic accumulation layer s_i

Deterministic transition operator P

Spectral boundedness condition:

rho(P) <= 1
|lambda| <= 1

Replay identity discipline:

B_A = B_B

Structural admissibility function:

adm_E(T) in {ALLOW, ABSTAIN}

SSSL does not:

• modify physical laws
• modify domain equations
• alter measured magnitude
• introduce predictive models
• simulate system dynamics
• perform optimization
• inject control authority
• guarantee safety outcomes

SSSL governs structural posture, not causation.


Conformance

An implementation conforms to the SSSL Open Standard if it:

Preserves magnitude exactly:

phi((m,a,s)) = m

Maintains finite alphabet closure:

|A4| = 4

Uses deterministic structural mapping F.

Produces deterministic transition operator P.

Satisfies spectral boundedness:

rho(P) <= 1
|lambda| <= 1

Produces byte-identical artifacts under independent replay:

B_A = B_B

Avoids probabilistic or tolerance-based arbitration.

Any implementation introducing:

• randomness
• probabilistic inference
• adaptive tuning
• dynamic alphabet expansion
• tolerance-based comparison
• nondeterministic output

does not conform to the SSSL Open Standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.


